<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38143b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38143b">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38143b"> 143(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> to above a horse / horse above</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[referring to Chinese]</font> in SHANG MA, <mark>to above a horse</mark>, i.e. to mount a horse, it <font color="green">[SHANG]</font> corresponds to a verb; in MA SHANG, <mark>horse above</mark>, i.e. on the horse, it corresponds to a preposition. <small> Sir Richard Paget, <a name="RPBP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RPBP"><cite title="source">Babel, or The Past, Present and Future of Human Speech</cite></a> (1930) 70</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
